# The hardest part for labeling came to analysis. For example:

    "same as the US, so clearly we’re not sh*t since we’ve done better than 90% of countries" - was chosen because it was not a reaction or a hot_topic but only boredering on analysis. I had to really think on if it would fit but since there were few analysis posts i had to make do.

    "Not really a fair comparison. When the US won 3rd, there were 13 teams and no 3rd Place match was played - they’re just ranked that way due to a retrospective ranking based on goal difference with Yugoslavia

    Turkey got 3rd place in a 32 team tournament and won the third place game"  -This as a great example of a good analysis post.

    "This game is playing out like the Paraguay one." This also is barely a discernible from hot_topic,reaction or analysis. But the way the sentence is structured made me see it more of as fitting for analysis than reaction.

# Here is a breakdown of how much each label takes up:

reaction: 127 / 222 ≈ 57.2%
analysis: 45 / 222 ≈ 20.3%
hot_take: 50 / 222 ≈ 22.5%

# Fine-Tuning Pipeline:

I used "llama-3.3-70b-versatile" via google colab. I used 3 epochs by loading distilbert-base-uncased because it is tuned to work well for small to medium amount of data. Had i had more than 200 rows then it would make sense to use something beyond 3.

# Baseline Comparison:

This was the system prompt I used:

        "You are classifying sports posts from r/soccer.
        Assign each post to exactly one of the following categories.

        analysis: Posts that explain something with reasoning, context, stats, tactics, or structured argument
        Example: "City kept overloading the right half-space because Arsenal’s midfield kept shifting too wide. That left space for the inverted fullback to step into midfield and control transitions."

        reaction: A reaction is a short or direct response that expresses emotion, judgment, or instant commentary about a post, event, or moment. It does not explain why something happened, build an argument, or use structured reasoning. It may include slang, humor, or agreement/disagreement, but stays surface-level.

        Example: "I can’t believe he missed that 💀"

        hot_take: Opinionated claims, debates, or ideological pushes without structured evidence (or with selective evidence used to win argument).
        Example: "People overrate Haaland’s overall game — he scores a lot, but he doesn’t contribute much in build-up play, and that limits him in big matches."

        Respond with ONLY the label name.
        Do not explain your reasoning.

        Valid labels:
        analysis
        reaction
        hot_take"

