# 3 wrong predictions analyzed:

--- #1 ---
Text: Because he had zero impact on the play, him attempting to play the ball isn’t relevant if there’s no impact on the play and there clearly wasn’t.
True: analysis
Predicted: reaction (confidence: 0.37)

This is can fit a either reaction or analysis but the reason it got reaction is most likely due to reaction being over represented in the dataset.

--- #2 ---
Text: In that case by default everyone is evil till proven otherwise. So the threshold for judgement is now whether or not you told the world you're evil. In which case Musk still qualifies.
True: hot_take
Predicted: reaction (confidence: 0.37)

Again this is most likely due to reaction being over represented while for the other two i had to really search for good balancing examples.

--- #3 ---
Text: Since Pru Pru's Puskas contender in 2022.
True: analysis
Predicted: reaction (confidence: 0.37)

This one is really neither and to me it highlights how the quality of data is more important than quantity. It means nothing if the data is bad on context.

The gap i am seeing is that getting good source of high quality examples and labeling them to be as obvious as possible as to the label's intent will lead to good outcome. However if the user labels it only to fullfill a quantity criteria than the following predictions will be poor since the examples its trained on are bad.The examples im drawing from are the three above. They are perfect examples.

Predictions with confidence above 0.7 were correct most of the time, while predictions below 0.5 were often incorrect. This suggests the model is weakly calibrated and tends to assign low confidence across most examples which is how 14/33 was achieved during error analysis.

To me the most obvious pattern of the errors was that it kept predicting reaction when the true label was hot take/analysis. That to me tells that reaction is over represented and the other two need more data. Beyond that some of reactionary data has one word comments as I took the 200 posts too literally at first run.

